revision.text:
[[File:Tenpaku Iwakura Site, zentai-1.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|天白磐座遺跡 概観}}{{small|左に西岩（岩A）、右に東岩（岩B）、中央奥に北岩（岩C）。}}]] '''Tenpaku Iwakura Site''' (天白磐座遺跡) is an ancient {{ill|ritual site|ja|祭祀遺跡|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Hamamatsu|ja|浜松市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hamanaku Ward|ja|浜名区|12=draft|12=draft}}, Inasa-chō, Ii-no-ya, Shizuoka Prefecture. It has been designated as a Shizuoka Prefectural Historic Site (official designation: "Ii Shrine Precinct Site").
It is a place of the {{ill|Tenpaku faith|ja|天白信仰|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview == [[File:Ii-jinja, haiden-2.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|{{ill|Ii Shrine|ja|渭伊神社|12=draft|12=draft}}}}{{small|The Tenpaku Iwakura Site is located on the mountain behind the shrine.}}]] Located in western Shizuoka Prefecture, the site is situated atop Yakushiyama, a conical hill with an elevation of 41.75 meters, behind {{ill|Ii Shrine|ja|渭伊神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, an {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft|12=draft}}-listed shrine, in the small basin of Iinoya formed by the Jingūji and Iinoya Rivers. The site features a cluster of massive rocks that served as {{ill|Iwakura rock|ja|磐座|lt=Iwakura rocks|12=draft|12=draft}} (Iwakura), believed to be the dwelling place of deities. The site was confirmed as a ritual site in 1988, and excavation was conducted in 1989.
The Iwakura consists of three large rocks: the western rock (A), eastern rock (B), and northern rock (C). Below the western rock’s western wall, numerous ritual artifacts, including over 200 hand-formed pottery pieces from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, talc magatama, iron weapons, and tools, as well as artifacts from the late Kofun to mid-Heian period, were unearthed. Between the western and eastern rocks, relics associated with later ritual practices, including {{ill|sutra mound|lt=sutra mounds|ja|経塚|12=draft|12=draft}}, were discovered, indicating continuous ritual significance through the mid-Heian period.
The site's location at the junction of two rivers suggests a connection to water-source rituals. The primary participants in these rituals are believed to be associated with the lineage of local rulers, evidenced by Kofuns such as {{ill|Kitaoka Ōtsuka Kofun|ja|北岡大塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} and other nearby tombs. Some theories propose that {{ill|Ii Shrine|ja|渭伊神社|12=draft|12=draft}} originated as an extension of Iwakura rituals, though this remains debated.
In 1992, the site was designated as the "Ii Shrine Precinct Site," a Shizuoka Prefectural Historic Site.
== Archaeological History == * 1988: Identified as a ritual site through the distribution of hand-formed pottery during a local survey. * 1989: Excavation conducted by {{ill|Doshisha University|ja|同志社大学|12=draft|12=draft}}. * 1992: Designated as a Shizuoka Prefectural Historic Site.
== Features == [[File:Tenpaku Iwakura Site, nishi-iwa.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Western Rock (A) Western Wall}}{{small|Excavations here revealed numerous Kofun-period ritual artifacts.}}]] The site consists of exposed and relocated {{ill|chert|ja|チャート|12=draft|12=draft}} rocks forming the sacred area. The primary rocks are: * '''Western Rock (A)''': The largest, measuring 10.3 meters north-south, 6.8 meters east-west, and 7.4 meters tall. * '''Eastern Rock (B)''': Rectangular, located 4 meters east of Rock A, measuring approximately 7 meters along its long axis, 4.1 meters along its short axis, and 5.2 meters in height. * '''Northern Rock (C)''': Triangular, situated slightly north of the central area, with a base of approximately 3.5 meters and a height of 2.7 meters.
Artifacts from ritual activities were concentrated in two locations: 1. Beneath the western wall of Rock A: Excavations revealed over 200 hand-formed pottery pieces, talc magatama, iron weapons, and Heian-period ceramics. 2. Between Rocks A and B: Relics such as sutra containers, mirrors, and earthenware were found, dating from the late Heian period to the Kamakura period.
== Cultural Properties == === Shizuoka Prefectural Cultural Properties === * '''Historic Site''': ** Ii Shrine Precinct Site - Designated on March 17, 1992<ref name="浜松市">[https://www.city.hamamatsu.shizuoka.jp/bunkazai/shitei/inasa/inasa/iijinjya.html Ii Shrine Precinct Site] (Hamamatsu City official website).</ref>.
== Related Facilities == * '''Hamamatsu City Regional Heritage Center''' (Hamamatsu City, Kita-ku, Inasa-chō, Iinoya) - Preserves and displays artifacts from the Tenpaku Iwakura Site.
